Creating two time-series data using zoo package

Only one kind of mobility can be produced once a time;taking mobility trend toward residence as an example

tsCA_Mobi <- zoo(#CA_Mobi$retail,
                 #CA_Mobi$grocery,
                 #CA_Mobi$parks,
                 #CA_Mobi$transit,
                 #CA_Mobi$workplace,
                 CA_Mobi$residence,
                 seq(from = as.Date("2020-02-16"), 
                 to = as.Date("2020-04-30"), by = 1))


summary(tsCA_Mobi)
##      Index              tsCA_Mobi    
##  Min.   :2020-02-16   Min.   :-1.00  
##  1st Qu.:2020-03-05   1st Qu.: 0.50  
##  Median :2020-03-24   Median :16.00  
##  Mean   :2020-03-24   Mean   :12.59  
##  3rd Qu.:2020-04-11   3rd Qu.:22.00  
##  Max.   :2020-04-30   Max.   :26.00
tsCAnew <- zoo(CA_newconfirm$new_confirmed, seq(from = as.Date("2020-02-21"), 
               to = as.Date("2020-05-12"), by = 1))

Plotting trends between mobility_residence and CA_daily new cases in ggplot

Comparing trends before and after “stay-at-home” order (2020-03-19 shown in dashline) in CA

Before the order(from early March),Californians were already increasing their morbility toward residence, meaning practing “stay -at-home” themselves.After the order, the mobility continue to increase, but to a lesser degree. It seems after the order, moblility fluctuate along with daily new cases

CAdata <-cbind(nortsCA_Mobi,nortsCAnew)
forZoo_CA1 <- fortify.zoo(CAdata,names = c("Index","Series","Value"),melt = TRUE)
  
s <- tibble(crazyfactor = ymd(c(forZoo_CA1$Index)), value=c(1:174)) %>%
mutate(crazyfactor = as.factor(crazyfactor))
forZoo_CA1 <- forZoo_CA1%>% 
  mutate(Series = as.character(Series)) %>% 
  mutate(Series = replace(Series, Series == 'nortsCA_Mobi', 'Residence'))%>%
  mutate(Series = replace(Series, Series == 'nortsCAnew', 'NewCases'))
p1<-ggplot(forZoo_CA1, aes(x = Index, y = Value, Group = Series)) +
    geom_line(aes(color = Series, linetype = Series)) +
    geom_vline(aes(xintercept = Index[which(levels(s$crazyfactor) == '2020-03-19')]), col =    "black",linetype = "longdash") +theme_bw()
plot(p1)
## Warning: Removed 17 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

#Lagged correlation between mobility and new cases to decide which lead which. There is a linear correlations between lagged mobility and daily new cases (p3), telling that as mobility toward homeplace increase, new cases increase. This weird outcome might be due to lack of early test and potential, uncontrolled communicty spread in Feb. even Jan. 2020. Yet, people’s practice of “stayin -at-home” is also led by daily new cases. The positive correlation taper with longer lagged day of new cases (p4)

p2 <-ccf (tsCA_Mobi,tsCAnew) 

p3 <-lag2.plot(tsCA_Mobi,tsCAnew,14) 

p4 <-ccf (tsCAnew,tsCA_Mobi) 

p5 <-lag2.plot(tsCAnew,tsCA_Mobi,14)

contrasting trends of mobility toward residence and new cases in Florida

Similar to Florida, before the order (on Apirl 3rd showed in black dashline), people already tended to stay at home when new cases increased. The mobility is more sensitive to new cases than to the order, even after the order implementation

FLdata <-cbind(nortsFL_Mobi,nortsFLnew)
forZoo_FL1 <- fortify.zoo(FLdata,names = c("Index","Series","Value"),melt = TRUE)
s1 <- tibble(crazyfactor = ymd(c(forZoo_FL1$Index)), value=c(1:174)) %>%
  mutate(crazyfactor = as.factor(crazyfactor))
  forZoo_FL1 <- forZoo_FL1%>% 
  mutate(Series = as.character(Series)) %>% 
  mutate(Series = replace(Series, Series == 'nortsFL_Mobi',    'ResideceTrend'))%>%
  mutate(Series = replace(Series, Series == 'nortsFLnew', 'NewCases'))
ggplot(forZoo_FL1,aes(x = Index, y = Value, Group = Series))+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = Index[which(levels(s1$crazyfactor) == '2020-04-03')]), col = "black",linetype = "longdash") +
  geom_line(aes(color = Series, linetype = Series))+ theme_bw()
## Warning: Removed 33 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

# lagged correlations between mobility and new cases in Florida # On lagged 11 days of mobility(p7,r=0.34) , it shows a trend that increased mobility toward homeplace led a decrease in daily new cases. Moreover, lagged news cases (p9,from 0 to -7) is still correlated with individuals’ behavior of staying at home

p6 <- ccf(tsFL_Mobi,tsFLnew)

p7 <- lag2.plot(tsFL_Mobi,tsFLnew,14)

p8 <- ccf(tsFLnew,tsFL_Mobi)

p9 <- lag2.plot(tsFLnew,tsFL_Mobi,14)

Oppose to our hypothesis, from the avaiable datasets, mobility alone cannot be used to predict future new cases. Instead, lagged new cases led the patterns of mobility. Policy lagged laymen’s reaction but helps maintaining people at home. Long term dynamics should be recoreded between mobility and new cases when “stay-at-home” eased in the future.
